2033 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
STYLE: GARDENS; THE HARD STUFF; IT'S EASY TO PLANT A LYRICAL LANDSCAPE, BUT 
DESIGNERS SEE BEAUTY IN A GARDEN'S BUILT FORMS AS WELL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Susan Heeger 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 At first glance, the subject might seem about as dry as decomposed granite. 
Where's the poetry in a patio? Who cares what kind of stone goes into a pool 
deck, or whether a path's made out of dirt or rocks or even peanut shells? When 
Tennyson talked about the crannied wall, it was only to get to his real 
subject: the adorable, pluckable flower. 
</P>
<P>
 But let's face it. That flower would be nowhere without the wall. And Tennyson 
might never have found it without a proper path. Leave out the hardscape -- the 
term garden professionals give to a landscape's built elements -- and a 
garden's likely to be a sorry mess, a trackless wilderness. Without the 
whip-cracking of walls and walks and decks, not only do prize plants fall out 
of formation but space remains undefined and therefore unusable: So long 
lounging patio; goodby al fresco dining room. 
</P>
<P>
 In a city like Los Angeles, terraces are what allow us to carve flat space out 
of sheared hills; walls hold back craggy canyons and screen out the neighboring 
populace; paths and steps link the various levels of our landscapes and connect 
up our gardens and houses. What's more, the pavement we install reduces 
planting area, maintenance and water use -- appealing dividends in our 
fast-paced, drought-conscious environment. 
</P>
<P>
 Back in the 1950s, California landscape architect Thomas Church was 
unequivocal about the value of hardscape in the general scheme of life. He 
wrote: "Paving -- something hard and convenient underfoot -- has been man's 
concern ever since he came down out of the trees." 
</P>
<P>
 Beyond the merely practical, however, there's a way in which paving defines 
the quality of our connection to the earth. In his classic book, "Genius Loci," 
Norwegian architectural scholar Christian Norberg-Schulz recounts the 
experience of architect Gerhard Kallmann wandering his devastated childhood 
street in postwar Berlin: His family's house was gone, "and Mr. Kallmann felt 
somewhat lost. Then he suddenly recognized the typical pavement of their 
sidewalk: the floor on which he had played as a child. And he experienced a 
strong feeling of having returned home." 
</P>
<P>
 Perhaps there is poetry here after all. And a message for us in Southern 
California, where our own streets were recently piled high with quake rubble -- 
bricks and broken concrete -- literally the building blocks of our outdoor 
life. Most of this refuse was taken to landfills or ground up and recycled for 
highway construction. Maybe now as it disappears, and before we're back to 
absently walking our new driveways and burying garden walls in shrubbery, we 
should stop to appreciate the hard stuff and its role in binding us to the 
world. 
</P>
<P>
 Think of hardscape as a framework -- for outdoor space, for plants, for all 
the activities that go on in a garden. In some areas, it might shine forth as 
the star, as in the case of a beautiful reflecting pool or a back-yard gazebo. 
In others, it falls back: the picket fence that's smothered in wisteria, the 
brick path connecting the rose collection to the vegetable patch. 
</P>
<P>
 Always, hardscape should take its cue from the house, the style and lines of 
which it extends into the landscape. Amid shaggy plantings, an edge of wood or 
stone gives the eye a resting place. It also suggests an overarching, 
human-made order in which, to a degree, nature is shaped and subdued. 
</P>
<P>
 Church, an inspired pragmatist whose aim was to get people to live in their 
gardens, argued for simplicity in a landscape's built forms. "It may be the 
role of paving to remain calm," he suggested, "to be the common denominator and 
a foil for the excitement created by fences, steps, grass forms, brilliant 
flower combinations, foliage textures and distant views." 
</P>
<P>
 On the other hand, history is full of landscapes remembered as much for their 
show-stealing stonework as for their greenery. Picture the pebbled courts and 
terraces of the Generalife palace in Granada. Or the formal gardens of the 
Italian Renaissance, replete with sculpture, grand stairways, pergolas and 
splashing waterways. In California, early 20th-Century residents of Montecito 
used Spanish, Islamic and Italian models to adorn their estates with fabulous 
rills and water walls, mosaic garden seats and walled, secluded courts. 
</P>
<P>
 Of course, even then, most Californians could only dream of garden living on 
such a scale. Today, given the small size of a typical landscape plot and the 
high cost of labor and materials, most of our hardscape decisions are very 
basic. We need steps -- but where exactly? How many? Made of what? We'd like a 
patio to eat on -- but how big? What kind? 
</P>
<P>
 Beyond the economic factors, these decisions are shaped by considering the 
consequences of our choices. Nowhere is this more evident, says Santa Barbara 
landscape architect Isabelle Greene, than in the realm of water conservation. 
"The greatest hardscape trend I see now," she reports, "is the awareness of the 
need to use water wisely." 
</P>
<P>
 Since the late 1980s, when public concern about drought began to spread, 
clients of Greene and others in her field have requested less lawn and more 
extensive hardscape to substitute for greenery altogether. 
</P>
<P>
 Greene herself is widely known for imaginative swaps of stones for plants. She 
has used river rock "streams" instead of groundcover to suggest flowing water 
in a dry landscape, and she designs beds in abstract shapes and fills some with 
massed succulents, others with dry-laid stone, to give the effect of a mosaic. 
</P>
<P>
 "I like to take each situation, intuit its real essence and bring that essence 
out," says Greene. She cautions, though, against overreliance on hardscape to 
solve landscape problems: "In many cases, the land should be left alone. We 
need permeable, porous surfaces, and we'll be in trouble if we keep paving 
everything over." 
</P>
<P>
 Accordingly, she often designs minimal decking around a pool, allowing the 
water to shine from a small lawn like a mirror of the sky. She mixes hardscape 
materials too, fashioning steppingstones from giant Santa Barbara boulders, 
stairs from railroad ties and decks from wood, tile or rock imbedded in 
concrete. In one design for a garden in the Hope Ranch area of Santa Barbara, 
such a mix of materials not only helped to stabilize a hillside but also 
blended with heathery plantings that echoed the brambly local chaparral. Even a 
long stairway, made of wood ties and linking a series of water gardens, rests 
lightly on the land, appearing to float downhill. 
</P>
<P>
 Like Greene, Mark Rios, a Los Angeles architect of landscapes as well as 
buildings, sees a hardscape trend in people's growing sensitivity to the 
environment. "Our expectations have changed," he says. With land in short 
supply and space getting tighter, he sees L.A. "becoming more of an urbanized 
culture. We're finding more in less. Fifteen years ago, it might have taken a 
huge lawn to satisfy the need for meditation and contemplation that makes us 
garden. Today, you can take a 15-by-15-foot, walled, paved court, put one 
beautiful specimen plant in it and that's enough." 
</P>
<P>
 As gardens grow more minimal, paving often gets more elaborate -- or is at 
least more carefully chosen, both for practical and aesthetic reasons. Concrete 
has been a popular paving material for decades, but those concerned about water 
conservation might decide to make a patio floor with salvaged, broken concrete 
rather than a new slab. Impermeable to water, unbroken slab concrete results in 
runoff and waste. It is also, as Rios points out, hard underfoot and can be 
blinding in full sun. 
</P>
<P>
 Broken paving, interplanted with something fragrant such as chamomile or 
woolly thyme, changes the experience of a simple walk through the garden. So 
does gravel, which crunches pleasingly, diffuses light softly and also happens 
to be less expensive than poured concrete or asphalt. 
</P>
<P>
 In one of Rios' own projects, a walled, Mediterranean-style house that had 
been redesigned by L.A. architect Stephanos Polyzoides, Rios used gravel 
throughout to connect a variety of garden and outdoor living areas. Instead of 
designing a path that would run through a dining courtyard, a couple of shade 
gardens and a children's play yard, he created a continuous "floor" of crushed 
beige and pink desert stone that makes the small spaces seem larger and 
complements the warm stucco of the house. It also reduces planted area and sets 
off what greenery there is -- for example, the roses, herbs and bougainvillea 
that burst forth at the edges of the dining area. 
</P>
<P>
 While this garden may seem minimal enough for some observers, Rios concedes 
that there are others for whom any maintenance is too much. For them, hardscape 
offers an alternative to going without an outdoor retreat altogether. 
</P>
<P>
 Rios created just such a retreat in the Hollywood Hills for a man who traveled 
almost constantly. When he was home, he was bothered by noise from the busy 
street on which his house sat. A study in hardscape detail, the walled court 
Rios designed features a copper fountain spilling water into a concrete 
channel, a walkway of Arizona flagstone and a field of construction gravel, 
with some eucalyptus trees and purple hop bush on the periphery. As Rios 
describes it: "It's a simple, modern, Zen-style garden with nothing in it." 
</P>
<P>
 Of course, not everyone appreciates such spareness, nor does a garden with a 
lot of paving have to do without fluffy, conspicuous foliage. Arcadia landscape 
architect Raymond Hansen has designed a number of gardens in which extensive 
hardscape has done double duty retaining hillsides and creating living space, 
all amid lively, naturalistic planting. For Sheila and Gerald Mells of 
Brentwood's Kenter Canyon, Hansen's creative paving transformed an unusable 
slope into an entry courtyard, pool terrace and entertaining area that also 
holds up a hill. Hansen and his associate, Patricia Araiza, used concrete 
pavers seamed with grass to substitute for lawn and unify the garden spaces. 
For softness, they planted the slope informally -- in creeping star jasmine, 
kangaroo paw and lavender, with sycamores and Canary Island pines shutting out 
neighbors' homes and blending with nearby chaparral. The whole effect is of 
clean, simple space left slightly shaggy at the edges by design. 
</P>
<P>
 For those whose hankie-size Venice yards -- not to mention modest pocketbooks 
-- would be mismatched with the professionals' elegant manipulations of 
hardscape, there's always the slapdash exuberance of crazy paving. A 
time-honored practice, it is often used in cottage gardens and described 
skeptically by Russell Page in his book, "The Education of a Gardener." 
</P>
<P>
 An internationally known English garden designer, he attributed the method to 
"an uninformed taste for the picturesque . . . which drives even quite 
sophisticated amateurs to smash good paving slabs into fragments and, like 
Hansel and Gretel in the fairy tale, scatter trails of them across the garden." 
</P>
<P>
 But it doesn't have to be like that. Heidi Wianecki, a Pacific Palisades 
artist who also does interior and garden design work, calls herself "a trasher 
who makes junk out of junk." Far from starting with anything new or "good," 
Wianecki says she regularly drives local alleyways, on the lookout for 
discarded materials. 
</P>
<P>
 In just this way, Wianecki amassed enough material to create a street garden 
and a courtyard in front of her house, a terrace behind it and even a 32-foot 
staircase of railroad-tie steps inlaid with all manner of cracked tile, brick 
and crockery. "It's cheap and I can do it myself," she explains, adding that 
she appreciates the spontaneity of a random pattern. 
</P>
<P>
 With scented groundcovers and herbs interplanted among the courtyard tiles and 
bird-seeded gazanias sprouting along the staircase, Wianecki's paving job is 
even wilder than Page imagined. For Wianecki, though, "it's experiential. It 
helps my mind wander." 
</P>
<P>
 For the rest of us, it's a lively model for finding and keeping -- for 
discovering new meaning among the ruins rather than throwing them away. 
Timeworn, blunt at the edges, nicked and scarred by long-gone feet and hands, 
Wianecki's crazy quilt could be what her own children recognize -- what brings 
them home -- as they stand on a corner in Los Angeles 50 years from now. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
