<HEADLINE>
<P>
LOS ANGELES CITY HALL JOURNAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MICHAEL KRIKORIAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A summary of selected City Hall actions last week that affect the Westside. 
CITY COUNCIL 
</P>
<P>
 * PROPERTY DAMAGE SUIT -- Authorized the city controller to pay $459,806 to 
James and Shirley Meinel for damage to their Hollywood Hills home caused by the 
Bureau of Street Maintenance.The Meinels' home partially slid off its 
foundation as maintenance bureau crews were removing mud, rocks and debris from 
Mulholland Drive after heavy rains last year. The controller was also 
authorized to pay $435,194 to the Meinels' lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
 * TREE PLANTING -- Approved the closure of Genesee Avenue between 25th and 
26th Streets on Nov. 5 from 8 a.m. to 1 p.m. for a tree planting program. HOW 
THEY VOTED 
</P>
<P>
 * PHOENIX HOUSE -- Approved a resolution that will allow Phoenix Houses of 
California Inc. to receive $10 million in California state bonds for the 
construction and remodeling of two drug rehabilitation centers, one at 500 
Ocean Front Walk in Venice and the other at 11600 Eldridge Ave. in Lake View 
Terrace. State officials wanted City Council approval before providing funding. 
Councilwoman Ruth Galanter said: "In Venice, where almost everyone complains 
about almost everything, I have never heard one complaint about Phoenix House." 
</P>
<P>
 Passed: 11-0. 
</P>
<P>
 Voting yes: Marvin Braude, Galanter, Jackie Goldberg, Nate Holden, Mark 
Ridley-Thomas. Absent: John Ferraro, Zev Yaroslavsky. MICHAEL KRIKORIAN 
</P>
