<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA ELECTIONS / THE LEGISLATURE; A CHANGING OF THE OLD GUARD IN 
SACRAMENTO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARK GLADSTONE and JERRY GILLAM, TIMES STAFF WRITERS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The 101 contests for state Assembly and Senate seats on the Nov. 8 election 
ballot are ushering in a new era in California legislative politics. 
</P>
<P>
 After wielding influence in the powerful Assembly Speaker's post for a record 
14 years, Willie Brown (D-San Francisco) is running for his seat in the lower 
house for the last time. Brown will be leaving the Assembly after two more 
years, forced out by voter-approved term limits. 
</P>
<P>
 The election also serves as a moment of truth for new Senate President Pro Tem 
Bill Lockyer (D-Hayward), who is struggling to maintain Democratic control of 
the upper house in the face of a strong challenge from Republican candidates, 
some of whose campaigns are fueled by contributions from the religious right. 
</P>
<P>
 As part of the changing of the guard in the Capitol, spurred by term limits, 
27 incumbents decided to retire or run for higher office. 
</P>
<P>
 And perhaps more important for the future than the stature of those departing, 
their replacements will increasingly mirror the state's diversity, with women 
and Latinos expected to enhance their numbers and be joined by the first openly 
gay state legislator. 
</P>
<P>
 Although Democrats believe they will maintain their majorities in both houses, 
the potentially volatile anti-Democratic mood of voters has candidates worrying 
and raising large amounts of money to win their elections. 
</P>
<P>
 Republicans see a banner year, with dislike of President Clinton weighing down 
his fellow Democrats, even those at the state level. Democrats say that 
California voters will follow their traditional independent pattern and zigzag 
down the ballot, not voting a straight party line. 
</P>
<P>
 Underscoring the anxiety, Speaker Brown, who bankrolls many campaigns, not 
surprisingly has urged all Democratic hopefuls to walk precincts. 
</P>
<P>
 "I am encouraging everyone to walk and campaign and do everything that they 
did to first get them up here," Brown said. 
</P>
<P>
 But the Speaker is not following his own advice. "I don't need to," Brown 
said. "If I walked precincts, it would take away from the time I spend raising 
money for other Assembly Democratic candidates." 
</P>
<P>
 Stoking the uncertainty is the fact that voters are much more focused on the 
glitzier races at the top of the ballot than on low-profile contests for all 80 
Assembly seats and 21 of the Senate's 40 seats. 
</P>
<P>
 In the Assembly, among the Democratic hopefuls expected to win -- and add a 
new dimension -- are Santa Monica law professor and former television actress 
Shelia Kuehl, who would be the first openly gay member of the Legislature, and 
attorney Kevin Murray, who, with his father, Assemblyman Willard H. Murray Jr. 
(D-Paramount), would form the first father-son duo to serve simultaneously in 
the same house. 
</P>
<P>
 The rookie ranks also are likely to include Republican farmer Tom J. Bordonaro 
Jr. of Paso Robles, who uses a wheelchair and is expected to capture a Central 
Coast Assembly seat vacated by a GOP incumbent who is running for Congress. 
</P>
<P>
 The Assembly Rules Committee has agreed to spend at least $85,000 in tax money 
to make Capitol offices more accessible for him and meet federal disability 
standards. 
</P>
<P>
 The outcomes of many races, however, are far less certain. Indeed, campaign 
strategists say that voters only begin to focus on legislative candidates in 
the final days before the election, when they receive a blizzard of targeted 
mail largely underwritten by contributions from special interests with business 
before the Legislature. 
</P>
<P>
 The campaigns are laced with themes about cracking down on crime, controlling 
illegal immigration, regulating gambling and the rising age of some entrenched 
incumbents, especially in the Senate. 
</P>
<P>
 "Voters know exactly what they're going to do: kill politicians. They're just 
deciding which ones," said veteran Democratic campaign strategist Richie Ross. 
</P>
<P>
 Hoping to capitalize on voter antipathy toward politicians, Assembly 
Republican Leader Jim Brulte of Rancho Cucamonga said he hopes the Republicans 
can pick up two or three seats. Democrats now hold a 47-33 edge over 
Republicans in the Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
 Brulte also said that he believes there are four Democratic incumbents in 
serious trouble. They are Assembly members Bob Epple of Cerritos and rookies 
Betty Karnette of Long Beach, Julie Bornstein of Palm Desert and Tom Connolly 
of Lemon Grove. All four won narrow election in 1992, as fellow Democrat 
Clinton carried California in the presidential election. Perhaps the most 
vulnerable Democrat of the lot is Connolly. In a 30-second TV commercial, the 
affable Connolly asks voters for a second chance even though he admits to 
having been a cocaine addict, a failed husband, a deadbeat dad, a tax 
delinquent and a failed businessman. He is being challenged by Republican Steve 
Baldwin, who barely lost to Connolly in 1992 before the assemblyman's problems 
were well known. 
</P>
<P>
 Democrats, meanwhile, are eyeing the seat now held by freshman Assemblyman 
Bill Hoge (R-Pasadena), who has raised tens of thousands of dollars from 
gambling interests. Democratic campaign consultants maintain that he is 
vulnerable to a challenge from Bruce Philpott, a retired police officer who 
served as Pasadena police chief for two years. Hoge has received $30,000 from 
the Allied Business PAC, the political action committee formed by Orange County 
Sen. Rob Hurtt and conservative Christian businessmen, to elect conservatives. 
Since 1992, it has reported giving more than $1.7 million to candidates. 
</P>
<P>
 Lockyer has deplored the activities of Hurtt and his group, saying they seek 
to establish a religious oligarchy. Hurtt has scoffed at the assertion, 
describing himself merely as a conservative who opposes abortions and favors 
school vouchers. 
</P>
<P>
 Lockyer has sought to drum up financial support for Democrats in the Senate, 
where Republicans see their best chance in years to cut into Democrat strength. 
</P>
<P>
 Now, the lineup is 22 Democrats, 15 Republicans, two independents and one 
vacancy because of the conviction on federal political corruption charges and 
subsequent resignation of former Sen. Frank Hill (R-Whittier). A special 
election to fill Hill's seat also is being held Nov. 8. 
</P>
<P>
 Of the 21 seats up for grabs this November, Democrats hold 14. Two Latino 
Assembly members, Democrats Richard Polanco of Los Angeles and Hilda Solis of 
El Monte, are expected to coast to easy victories in safely Democratic Senate 
districts. 
</P>
<P>
 But in swing districts, the picture is different. 
</P>
<P>
 "Right now, Republicans are leading and Democrats are faltering in a lot of 
districts," GOP Senate strategist Ron Rogers said. But he is not predicting a 
Republican takeover this year in the upper house and acknowledges that the 
final 10 days of the campaign is really "when the struggle is on for the hearts 
and minds of voters." 
</P>
<P>
 Still, half a dozen Senate seats are being heavily contested from Redding to 
Riverside. 
</P>
<P>
 One pitched battle to replace retiring Sen. Gary K. Hart (D-Santa Barbara) 
features Assembly Speaker Pro Tem Jack O'Connell (D-Carpinteria), an energetic 
campaigner, squaring off against Steve MacElvaine, a Republican former San Luis 
Obispo County supervisor and onetime member of the California Coastal 
Commission. MacElvaine is painting the boyish-looking O'Connell, 43, as a 
career politician and the election is considered a tossup. 
</P>
<P>
 In another open Senate seat held by a Democrat, freshman Assemblyman Ray 
Haynes (R-Murrieta) is matched against Democrat Kay Ceniceros, a longtime 
Riverside County supervisor. Staunch conservative Haynes is banking on strong 
financial help from the Christian right to defeat Ceniceros in the district in 
which Republicans hold a registration edge over Democrats. Haynes has received 
$64,000 this year from the Allied Business political action committee, 
according to state-required reports. 
</P>
<P>
 A second contest expected to be a showdown between Democrats and the religious 
right is taking place in a district that stretches from the edge of San 
Francisco Bay to the Oregon border. Sen. Maurice Johannessen (R-Redding), who 
was elected in a special election last year, is facing a stiff challenge from 
Yolo County Supervisor Michael H. McGowan, who is relying on monetary support 
from Lockyer. 
</P>
<P>
 Another incumbent conservative Republican facing a strong, well-financed 
challenge is Sen. Phil Wyman (R-Tehachapi). Wyman last year won a special 
election but is seeking a full term in a more heavily Democratic farm belt 
district redrawn in reapportionment. Like last year, Wyman is facing 
Assemblyman Jim Costa (D-Hanford). 
</P>
<P>
 One of the hottest Senate contests in the Los Angeles area pits Sen. Ralph 
Dills (D-El Segundo), first elected to the Legislature in 1938, against 
Republican rival David Barrett Cohen, a Redondo Beach businessman who is part 
Samoan and is Jewish, who reports receiving a $20,000 donation from Hurtt. One 
of the Legislature's flashiest dressers, the blue-haired, saxophone-playing 
Dills, 84, uses the campaign slogan "Too Old to Quit."' 
</P>
<P>
 Times staff writer Carl Ingram contributed to this story. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA102394-0343 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 091543 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
